 we need 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}(\rho)=1$
\end_inset

,
 which forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 to be (equivalent to) a probability measure —
 automatically sigma–finite.
 So in the standard Hilbert space formulation,
 non–sigma–finite measures cannot give density matrices directly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\emph on
KMS states and Type III von Neumann algebras.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Consider quantum statistical mechanics at inverse temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The Gibbs state is formally 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{\beta}=\frac{e^{-\beta H}}{Z},\qquad Z=\mathrm{Tr}(e^{-\beta H}).
\]

\end_inset

For a finite system,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z<\infty$
\end_inset

 and everything works.
 In the thermodynamic limit (infinite volume),
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 There is no normalizable density matrix.
 The "measure" 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mu(m)=e^{-\beta E_{m}}\,d(\mathrm{spectrum})$
\end_inset

 is not finite.
 The resolution is to abandon the density–matrix formulation entirely and work at the level of the observable algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

.
 A state becomes a positive linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega:\mathcal{A}\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\mathbf{1})=1$
\end_inset

.
 The thermal equilibrium condition is encoded not by a density matrix but by the KMS condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega\!\left(A\,\sigma_{i\beta}^{\omega}(B)\right)=\omega(BA)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{\omega}$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar allowbreak
 is the modular automorphism group.
 This is the correct replacement for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}(\rho AB)=foobar$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
