\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
For a finite system with Gibbs state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=e^{-\beta H}/Z$
\end_inset

,
 the KMS condition follows from cyclicity of the trace.
 The time evolution automorphism is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}\left(B\right)=e^{iHt}Be^{-iHt}$
\end_inset

,
 so analytically continuing to imaginary time gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i\beta}(B)=e^{-\beta H}Be^{\beta H}$
\end_inset

 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega\!\left(A\,\sigma_{i\beta}(B)\right)=\frac{1}{Z}\mathrm{Tr}\!\left(e^{-\beta H}A\,e^{-\beta H}B\,e^{\beta H}\right)=\frac{1}{Z}\mathrm{Tr}\!\left(A\,e^{-\beta H}B\right)
\]

\end_inset

Independently:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega(BA)=\frac{1}{Z}\mathrm{Tr}\!\left(e^{-\beta H}BA\right)=\frac{1}{Z}\mathrm{Tr}\!\left(A\,e^{-\beta H}B\right)
\]

\end_inset

The KMS condition is thus precisely the statement that cyclicity of trace,
 which is elementary for finite systems,
 survives as a well–defined algebraic identity in the thermodynamic limit even when 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to\infty$
\end_inset

 and no actual 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 exists.
