\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
DHR morphisms require that the charge be localizable in a bounded region —
 the field creating the charge must look like the vacuum outside some compact set.
 This fails for electrically charged states in QED,
 because Gauss's law forces the electric field to extend to infinity.
 Every charged particle drags an infrared cloud of soft photons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Buchholz and Fredenhagen generalized DHR to allow charges localized in spacelike cones rather than bounded regions.
 In this framework,
 different asymptotic photon cloud configurations —
 parameterized by classical asymptotic field data,
 which is a function space —
 give rise to sectors labeled by an element of an infinite–dimensional space.
 This is genuinely uncountable.
 The Faddeev–Kulish dressing of electron states is a concrete realization:
 the dressing function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(k)$
\end_inset

 (specifying the soft photon coherent state) ranges over an uncountable function space,
 and each inequivalent 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

