\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
The countability in the σ–algebra axiom is not merely convenient —
 it is load–bearing for completeness.
 The proof that L² is a Hilbert space (not just a pre–Hilbert space) requires completeness,
 i.e.,
 every Cauchy sequence converges.
 The standard proof (Riesz–Fischer) goes:
 Given a Cauchy sequence {fₙ},
 extract a subsequence with ‖fₙₖ₊₁ − fₙₖ‖ < 2⁻ᵏ,
 define g = Σₖ |fₙₖ₊₁ − fₙₖ|,
 show g ∈ L² via Monotone Convergence (which requires σ–additivity),
 conclude the series converges a.e.
 and in L².
 Without σ–additivity (countable additivity),
 monotone convergence fails,
 and L² need not be complete.
 With only a finitely additive measure on an algebra of sets,
 you get a pre–Hilbert space whose completion would require an external argument.
