\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
A vector lattice L ⊆ {f:
 M → ℝ} of "elementary" integrable functions,
 closed under ∧ and ∨
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
A positive linear functional I:
 L → ℝ (the proto–integral) The Stone condition:
 if fₙ ↓ 0 pointwise in L,
 then I(fₙ) → 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
From these,
 one constructs the full L² theory without ever explicitly writing down a σ–algebra.
 The σ–algebra of measurable sets emerges as a theorem.
 So the σ–algebra requirement is not so much dropped as it is derived rather than postulated.
 This is a logically cleaner foundation in some contexts (e.g.,
 when you have a natural space of test functions but no obvious σ–algebra).
