\emph on
What Is Solidly Established
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Squeezed states in heavy–ion collisions is a genuine research area.
 The key observable is Hanbury Brown–Twiss (HBT) interferometry —
 two–pion correlations in momentum space.
 The connection to squeezing was made explicitly by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Yuen (1976) and subsequently Walls and Milburn established the general squeezed state formalism in quantum optics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Aichelin and Bertsch (1985) and others applied two–particle correlations to heavy–ion physics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Andreev,
 Betman,
 and Siemens —
 and more explicitly Sinyukov and collaborators in the 1990s —
 noted that the pion source in heavy–ion collisions could produce squeezed coherent states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
The most explicit connection between squeezed pion states and HBT correlations was developed by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Agarwal and collaborators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Cernigoi,
 Fabbri and others in the Italian school
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Most explicitly:
 M.
 Asakawa,
 T.
 Csörgő,
 and M.
 Gyulassy —
 "Little Bang Squeezed Pion States" —
 who argued that back–to–back pion correlations (as opposed to same–direction HBT correlations) are a direct signature of squeezed vacuum states produced in the quark–gluon plasma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\emph on
The Back–to–Back Correlation Signature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
This is the most concrete physical prediction.
 A squeezed vacuum at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 generates correlations between modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 —
 exactly the off–diagonal Bogoliubov structure we identified.
 This produces an enhancement in the back–to–back pion pair distribution:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C(\mathbf{k},-\mathbf{k})=1+\left|\frac{\langle a(\mathbf{k})a(-\mathbf{k})\rangle}{\langle a^{\dagger}(\mathbf{k})a(\mathbf{k})\rangle}\right|^{2}>1
\]

\end_inset

This is distinct from the usual HBT effect which correlates 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 pairs.
 The back–to–back signal is a direct quantum signature of the Bogoliubov mixing of the vacuum.
\emph default

