\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wow!
 That's quite the table of contents!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Statistical physics overlaps economics,
 which,
 you could say,
 is the statistics of a game (involving money) played on a network.
 For those readers who think economics is boring,
 rest assured,
 so is statistical physics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both of these overlap with something that is apparently called "experimental philosophy" these days,
 which is,
 as far as I can tell,
 mathematical computer simulations of interacting agents playing games with one–another.
 The prototypical form is the prisoner's dilemna played on a network.
 I recall a fun interactive game,
 from a few decades ago,
 by Nicky Case at ncase.me that illustrated various basic results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I presume that it is not lost on anyone that last year's Nobel Prize,
 handed out for large language models,
 was all about how statistical physics was applied to solve seemingly intractable issues in deep learning.
 And now we're spending a trillion dollars a year to built datacenters.
 Maybe even in space,
 if the billionaire futurists have their way.
 When I studied statistical physics in school,
 it never occurred to me that it might one day become a trillion–dollar industry.
 I think I missed the boat.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Back on Earth,
 we have the problem of equitably distributing wealth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
between cranks proclaiming nonsense about quantum zero–point energy,
 and the more legit,
 but still often-wrong contingent of,
 what shall I call them – earnest but midwit researchers who are less adept at chasing fame,
 glory,
 money,
 adulation or youtube stardom.
 The current economic system does not work for them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In large corporations,
 there are periodic layoffs to remove the "deadwood" – employees who apparently contribute little or nothing to the economic survival of the corporation.
 In longevity biomedicine,
 we talk of removing senescent cells:
 those that spew free radicals and induce inflammation.
  But what happens when these are people?
 Living,
 spiritual beings who want to get on with things?
 Or,
 in the present case,
 participants in scientific conferences at the edge of financial instability?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The statistical physics model I keep coming back to is Per Bak's "Abelian Sandpile".
 Drop grains of sand on a pile,
 and you eventually get avalanches.
 They come in all sizes.
 Usually small,
 sometimes medium,
 rarely large.
 This is called "1/f noise" (one–over–frequency) and is characteristic of network systems at the edge of a second–order phase transition.
 I like this model because you see it everywhere:
 water near the triple point ("critical opalescence"),
 but also biochemistry,
 biology,
 plants,
 animals,
 ecosystems and economics.
 Oh,
 and some neuroscientists talk about this too.
 Some claim to actually measure it,
 with neuron clamps or with MRI.
 Others theorize it to be a model of consciousness,
 thinking,
 common sense and decision-making.
 I can't keep up with all the novel ideas,
 or distinguish the rigorous ones from the flights of fancy,
 the important ones from the fraudulent ones.
  I do like the general outlines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Avalanches in ecology require more sophistication to describe.
 Forest ecologists note that forests regrow and appear to be healthier after a wild–fire.
 Is this what the future after Trump will be like?
 He is burning down so much of the old world,
 that perhaps it will be easier for the new world to take root and flourish?
 I can only hope.
 Or does it encourage noxious invasive species?
 To stick to the sand–pile analogy:
 after a particularly huge landslide,
 the mountain slope becomes much much more stable.
 Trump etal are shaking the ground so hard that maybe the final outcome will be a stabler system.
 I dunno.
  I see statistical physics where–ever I turn,
 but perhaps that is just me.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One area where we see accretion is at the frontiers of science.
 Vague thoughts and philosophical ruminations,
 soft and often wrong,
 lead to the preferential attachment of good ideas into the framework of "the known".
 Sometimes a new scientific discovery slots neatly into an edifice of the known,
 much like a jigsaw puzzle piece slots into a puzzle.
 Sometimes this is very literal:
 mathematical formulas have very specific,
 typed jigsaw connectors:
 they only connect to other math formulas in very strict,
 specific ways.
 Software is like this too:
 the c/c++/java function `int f(int x)` cannot be connected to a string.
 The jigsaw tabs prohibit it.
 Our villain of the day,
 Nassim Haramein,
 is villainous precisely because he abuses formulas in this way,
 connecting them where connections are not allowed.
 In other cases,
 say in philosophy,
 the fog is so thick that it's hard to see what connects to what.
 In other cases,
 say,
 medicine up through the 19th century,
 the system under study was so complicated that comprehension was nearly impossible.  Conferences,
 like your conference,
 Anton,
 on statistical physics,
 give me the willies,
 because I can already tell that a third of what will be published there will be just plain wrong,
 and another third will be not particularly insightful.
 But this is what humans do:
 make confused and confusing statements,
 often wrong.
 But knowledge does accrete.
 The avalanches,
 these we term the "scientific revolutions".
 The old edifice collapses,
 as it no longer can bear the weight of the new knowledge.
 The small avalanches,
 aka "wrong papers",
 "wrong insights",
 "incorrect proofs" are commonplace.
 1/f noise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Science works (or worked?
 Should I use the past tense?) because academic journals were an early form of social media,
 allowing the rapid spread of new ideas,
 while also moderating the truly bad ones via peer review.
 There's no peer review in twitter,
 facebook,
 bluesky.
 There's only hearts and likes. I fear that the global brain will continue to edge towards delerium until we find some effective way of modulating the delusions.
 Sorry,
 anti–vaxxers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another place where we see accretion is in what I call "the here and now".
 In case you haven't noticed,
 we are permanently jailed in the present,
 and are propelled at light speed from the past to the future.
 Please observe that the past doesn't exist:
 we cannot send any device into the past to take some photograph of how things used to be.
 We can only alter the present so as to fashion a record of the past,
 e.g.
 by inscribing letters into clay tablets.
 Or by inscribing memories into our neurons.
 The future also doesn't exist ...
 yet.
 The so–called "many–worlds" of quantum exists only in the here–and–now,
 in vacuum chambers and fiber optics,
 with wave-functions collapsing into the past at a furious pace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is the past a form of "platonic reality"?
 I suppose.
 It's not like the platonic reality of mathematics,
 where anyone can infer 2+2=4.
 Sometimes,
 you can infer the past:
 this is what police detectives do for a living.
 Usually,
 you cannot:
 CIA covert ops will remain secret forever,
 as will the events on the Mongolian steppes from some millenia ago.
 Although these are in our past causal light–cone,
 direct inference is blocked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is the past some large cardinal axiom (literally) ?
 Well,
 either it is,
 or it is not.
 If it is not,
 then you have to posit something that exists outside of the von Neumann universe:
 call it "God" or "machine elves" or "the human soul".  But then you have a recursive reductionist problem:
 if physical humans are "radio receivers" for souls from the great beyond,
 well,
 how does that work?
 And if you can start to explain that,
 you inevitably slip back into the domain of mathematics.
 So it seems that the past is some inaccessible,
 ineffable large cardinal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exactly how we use free will to shape the future and convert it into the past is perhaps the great unsolved problem in statistical physics.
 I ponder it intermittently.
 I should point out that quantum mechanics (quantum field theory) exists only in the here–and–now;
 the wave of freezing,
 moving from future to the past like ice-9,
 seems to have a "thickness":
 the range of time over which quantum is valid.
 This is femtoseconds for chemistry,
 minutes for vacuum chambers in physics labs,
 and billions of years for light reaching our eyes from distant galaxies (which arrive here in "zero time":
 the photons lie on the null light–cone.)  For example,
 in the famous "twin paradox",
 the twin arrives younger,
 but he arrives in the here–and–now,
 and not in the past.
 When the twins reunite,
 they reunite,
 co–exist,
 right now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another thing that exists "right now" is my consciousness.
 I can remember the past,
 but I am not conscious in the past,
 I am conscious only right now.
 My self–awareness also appears to exist in some noosphere:
 albeit in the kitchen,
 in front of my laptop,
 where I type this,
 but also in the space of ideas.
 What is this space of ideas?
 One answer is mumble mumble mumbo jumbo quantum.
 Another is to note that LLM's seem to "exist" on the surface of a billion–dimensional hypersphere (aka "the weight matrix").
 This weight matrix consists of floating point numbers (aka "real numbers").
 I would very much like to point out that quantum mechanics exists on the surface of a very high–dimensional complex–valued hypersphere (aka complex projective space CP(n) for n=10^80 particles in the visible universe)  So I'm quite happy to say "ah hah,
 that is the seat of consciousness:
 it is this ultra–high–dimensional hypersphere" (of course I would claim something like this,
 I'm that kind of guy.) But,
 and this is a big but:
 does it require the space to be complex–valued?
 Or can it be real?
 If it must be complex,
 and cannot be real,
 then LLM's can never have the sensation of consciously existing in the present.
 Kind of a hot topic,
 you know.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I'm entirely happy to ascribe the (very human,
 personal) sensation of "self" aware and alive in the here–and–now,
 to animals:
 certainly all of those animals in all those youtube shorts,
 but also,
 well,
 that octopus in that Netflix documentary "My Octopus Teacher" friggin awesome movie.
 Go watch it.
 I suspect that amoeba have consciousness as well,
 but assholes like to argue with me.
 I don't like arguing with them,
 because my communications style insults people.
 Oh well.
 Qualia,
 qualia.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Should I ascribe consciousness to a rock?
 Well,
 no.
 Perhaps consciousness only arises on one side of a phase transition,
 when a system is complex enough.
 Recall my description of "percolation" (the percolation of natural gas through fractured rock) in my earlier email.
 The percolation happens only when there is sufficient connectivity from one side to the other.
 So perhaps consciousness is like this too:
 some minimal amount of network connectivity is required.
 This is the statistical mechanics rebuttal to the philosophical idea of panpsychism.  The descartian notion of panpsychism says that its "qualia all the way down".
 (DesCartes called them "monads") The stat–mech reply is "its percolation".  Percolation of what?
 Of the future into the past?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with "mechanics" is that,
 well,
 it's so "mechanical".
 I'm trying to figure out how to slot "free will" into this wave of freezing from future to past,
 that we call the inescapable prison of the present.
 I'm working on it.
 I've attempted to staple statistical physics to quantum physics in a dozen different ways,
 none are satisfactory.
 My ideas are probably wrong.  But I'm working on it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So there you go,
 Anton -- my humble and belated submission for your conference.
 Best I can do on short notice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-- Linas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
23 April 2026
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Its quarter to ten,
 my evening has been ruined,
 my sister served white wine with dinner,
 and I do not feel like doing anything.
 So I spent the last hour doom–scrolling my news feed.
 Almost all of it seems pointless.
 It's been made worse by a Netflix documentary I watched a few days ago – something about gorillas,
 narrated by David Attenborough.
 Thoroughly depressing,
 thoroughly pointless.
 Gorillas are assholes.
 I knew this even before the show started playing.
 It only got worse.
 I mean,
 there are some abstractly interesting ideas:
 that gorillas communicate through body language:
 how they sit,
 hold their neck,
 where they face,
 when,
 during proximity,
 they decide it's OK to relax,
 and when to snub.
 Lots and lots of body language.
 Some of it,
 much of it,
 is readable to humans,
 since,
 after all,
 we are apes.
 I can watch this movie,
 and I can read that body language,
 I can see it.
 I spent a fair amount of time wondering how I would react in any of the situations.
 I'm sort of mediocre at body language;
 I've spent too much of my life leading the life of the mind (jeez,
 I only had three glasses of white wine on a full stomach and I already can no longer compose elegant sentences.
 How disappointing.
 It's two hours till midnight.
 I should be better tomorrow.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So anyway,
 interpreting the body language of gorillas is intellectually interesting.
 But for what?
 What's the point?
 I suppose if I was a gorilla,
 it would be kind of like if I was kind–of–drunk,
 didn't have a bank account,
 and was homeless.
 Didn't have much in the way of responsibilities,
 and mostly just lay around and eat and if I'm lucky,
 fuck,
 and mostly do nothing but body language all day long to express the utter pointlessness of my life.
 And that just came off as utterly depressing.
 No wonder gorillas are assholes.
 I'd be an asshole too,
 if I had nothing better to do.
 I'm already an asshole,
 as it is;
 being a gorillas would just make me a worser version of myself.
 Seriously.
 I've never contemplated suicide,
 and as a gorilla,
 I still wouldn't,
 but the intellectual me says:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuck no,
 obliviate this pointless existence.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 So I guess you could say I did not like the documentary.
 I mean,
 its OK,
 I guess but its depressing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the bad news is that it only gets worse.
 Almost every news headline from the last two or three days comes off as just more gorillas engaged in more meaningless posturing and chest–thumping and signaling of shifting allegiances by turning half–profile and cocking the neck.
 Congressmen,
 CEO's.
 News reporters and the objects of their reporting.
 They are all asshole gorillas behaving in assoholic ways,
 engaged in pointless,
 meaningless activities.
 Its thoroughly depressing.
 The news headlines,
 the news stories provide detailed documentation of any and every pathetic life.
 Pathos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's ick.
 Get it away from me.
 Scrape it off of me.
 I don't want that.
 I don't want to be part of that utterly pathetic drunken miasmatic pointless existence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I guess this means that I have gotten insight into the pointlessness of life in modern Western democratic capitalism,
 and the associated psychic crises associated with it.
 Some large percentage of the population wake up to find themselves in some intolerable situation,
 and don't know what to do about it.
 Aren't smart enough to figure a way out.
 The gorilla forced to be a loner in that documentary,
 this is a portrait miniature of the societal outcasts.
 The tribe that sticks together – they're the normies.
 Mostly.
 They figured out how live with one another.
 Mostly.
 How to enjoy one–another.
 Mostly.
 How to have an OK life,
 how to get by,
 how to live,
 if you're homeless,
 have the IQ of a stone–cold drunk,
 and have nothing better to do but to sleep in the rain and live in the trees of a mountaintop.
 I don't know if I should be empathic for them,
 or not.
 I could wax poetic,
 and write fervored lines of prose praising the humble life.
 Or I can condemn.
 The humble life has its place.
 Crissy Hines got it into a song lyric:
 lying in the gutter,
 looking at the stars.
 The gorillas are clearly in the gutter.
 They do not seem to be looking at the stars.
 I don't know if that is the fault of the film crew and the David Attenborough narration,
 or whether the gorillas are actually just like that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem here is that being alive is,
 well,
 an aspect of life.
 This seems entirely fine,
 and can be celebrated with youtube videos of cute little goats hopping up and down on hay bales.
 Or horses chasing one after another,
 clearly in love.
 Love makes my heart beat faster.
 I forgive all for love.
 Jane Austen's Pride and Prejudice tugs on my heart–strings no less than on those of any other fan.
 Life is worth celebrating.
 I advance arcane mathematical ruminations on how it could be modeled and made to function using algebraic insights.
 I can empathize with an amoeba in my finer moments.
 But gorillas are assholes.
 And,
 it seems,
 so are politicians and CEO's and pretty much everyone else we celebrate as the great leaders of Western society.
 It is thoroughly depressing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I don't know.
 I don't know how to reconcile this with my otherwise hopeful and positive feelings when enthralled by the awesomeness of life.
 I don't know what to do with that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The obvious solution is to just stop skimming my news feed.
 Out of sight,
 out of mind.
 But I'm skimming the news feed because I am actively avoiding the stress of dealing with my email.
 I fucking hate looking at my email.
 Each new email is a demand on my time,
 my attention.
 Each new email requires me to spend half a day,
 or more,
 doing something stupid,
 pointless,
 unpleasant and unrewarding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I suppose farmers in ancient Anatolia had plenty to do that was stupid and unpleasant;
 but the alternative was starving to death,
 and so I cannot call those activities pointless and unrewarding:
 one has to get by.
 But my email queue?
 Fuck me.
 The rewards are so abstract,
 hypothetical.
 I know if I don't deal with things,
 my life will slide downhill,
 and I will be sorry years,
 decades later.
 But dealing with things is ...
 painful.
 So I procrastinate.
 Just like,
 well,
 kind of almost everyone.
 And today's procrastination was skimming the news headlines.
 Tomorrow will be different.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There were two interesting headlines.
 One was about some super–radiant continuous–wave three–level lasers that have fantastically narrow beam widths (100 microHertz) aka long coherence lengths (quote:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

from Sun to Uranus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 – I guess 0.1 milliHertz is 1 over 10K seconds,
 or 3 light–hours,
 which is I guess the distance to Uranus.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This makes me think a bit about tinkering.
 My newsfeed comes with advertisements that encourage me to tinker with a Raspberry Pi.
 Or maybe tinker with some spectroscopic analyzer.
 Or some reagents for polypeptide chromatography.
 They do have me pegged as a science tinkerer,
 and I have spent most of life doing software tinkering.
 I seem to fall into it naturally.
 So I thought about tinkering an AI engineer that would build me a supper–radiant continuous–wave laser that I could then use in a super–accurate clock.
 Cause clocks are interesting,
 they expose the workings of relativity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course,
 I should return to tinkering with my symplectic manifolds and Unruh radiation.
 But I did not because (a) white wine,
 and (b) this is a sufficiently large project that if I fell into it,
 it would stop me from doing (facing) some of the actually important tasks I've been procrastinating on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other tinkering project was inspired by an article in the Financial Times.
 It was about Europe's capitulation in the face of the SpaceX IPO.
 The author seems to say that he ran 150 iterations of an experiment,
 where he had some collection of agents,
 modelling Euro decision makers,
 making 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rational
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 decisions in the process of setting up the EU space program.
 In every iteration,
 the outcome was perverse:
 even though each agent acted rationally,
 the outcome was bad.
 The EU lost,
 and SpaceX won.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This news story is what inspired me to open my laptop and write this diary entry.
 The above,
 about apes,
 was a diversion.
 The real deal is this:
 the algorithmic simulation of multi–agent geo–political,
 economic decision makers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is this the future?
 Could I build a multi–agent political model of Texas,
 and see if I could force Greg Abott's hand with small steps that pin him into a corner?
 A kind of chess computer,
 but for (geo–)politics?
 Of course,
 he could hire even more geeks to build an even more sophisticated political–chess computer,
 and attempt to enforce his political predilections on the rest of us.
 I'm not sure,
 I suppose Machiavelli must have made analogies between chess and politics,
 and if not him,
 then many others.
 I mean,
 OMG,
 look at the fucking shape of the chess pieces.
 Their names.
 But we have entered,
 only now,
 the era of practical geo–political chess computers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I did read,
 more than two decades ago,
 a slashdot story about the CIA working on version three of their geo–political modeling system.
 That was then,
 this is now.
 I could conceivably harness Claude Code and hand–build a home–brew geopolitcal chess computer.
 It's within reach of not just nation–states,
 but individual congressmen and senators.
