\begin_layout Standard
Peter's reply seems reasonable.
 I suggest an approach inspired from biology and sociology.
 It is necessarily multi-layered.
 Let me draw an analogy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Police forces patrol and protect against individual criminals,
 engaged in a vast variety of crimes and misdemeanors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* The FBI tackles problems too big for local police forces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* A standing army protects the nation state.
 The army is (should be) rarely or never active;
 but the CIA (and NSA) (and State Dept) do most of the actual work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* At the other end:
 our bodies have an immune system protecting us against bacterial invaders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* We have medical doctors for those issues that our bodies cannot handle on their own.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* Careful analysis of the immune system reveals a multi–layered,
 structured,
 fractal defense system,
 with various systems being either slow,
 or exponentially fast response systems.
 Some bacterial infections are conquered by massively out–producing the bacteria:
 spawning two white blood cells for every one new bacterium.
 Exponentially doubling.
 In the military,
 they call this the "Lanchester square law collapse".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There won't be one super–massive AI/AGI/LLM,
 there will be many.
 Some will be large,
 some small.
 Some will be highly organized (like our bodies composed of cooperating parts:
 skin,
 muscles,
 bones) while others are only loose confederations (like mold growing on a tree stump).
 Small systems (e.g.
 some AI embedded in your electric meter) will have millisecond response times;
 but they will be far too stupid to be "loving" or "maternal" in the way mammals (or birds) are.
 They could still be dangerous,
 anyway.
 We will have to monitor them.
 The big–giant systems ...
 well,
 they are slower but far more powerful.
 I guess Hinton and others think exclusively of these large systems,
 but fail to fully encompass the intermediate–size,
 intermediate–scale systems.
 I mean,
 I have a frigging mid–range/high–endish GPU in my desktop computer,
 and could unleash a rather slow and primitive,
 but entirely dangerous system;
 nothing stops me (but my own conscience).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also:
 the danger is not just AI's;
 but human–AI combos.
 I'm reading Umberto Eco's "Cemetery of Prague" and it's a portrait of cold,
 casual,
 disinterested evil at the end of the 19th century:
 Simoninis does it for the money;
 otherwise,
 he just does not really care about the harm that he does.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In short:
 human bodies and human societies have multi–layered multi–fractal hierarchical defenses.
