\begin_layout Standard
Some years ago I wrote a paper saying that CCG (combinatorial categorial grammar) is identical to LG (link grammar).
 And this is mostly true.
 In that paper,
 I gave a formal correspondence for some 90% of the features in both.
 An isomorphism,
 of sorts.
 Then I noted,
 at the end,
 the remaining 10% of the isomorphism.
 one has multiple choices.
 One can complete the mapping several ways,
 having pros and cons to each.
 Most or all of these completions were not entirely satisfying,
 and there was not any one choice that towered over the rest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the time that I wrote that text,
 this irked me.
 A week or two ago,
 it shot into my head that this situation resembled various cases in mathematics,
 where some sort of morphism or some homotopy is blocked by some sort of (global) structure.
 And that this blockage is important:
 the sphere is not homotopic to a torus.
 This is not an annoyance,
 but the symptom of something fundamental.
 So perhaps here,
 too.
 Perhaps I should go back and quantify the failure to align.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A lot of what I talk (think) about in AI/AGI research has to do with representations:
 how can I represent structures and relations observed in the exterior world?
 To what degree are different representations isomorphic,
 and when are they not?
 Representations,
 at the level of algebraic statements,
 at the level of lambda calculus,
 at the level of axioms and inference rules,
 can generally be homotopically transformed into one–another.
 Except when they cannot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the software point of view,
 I want to have two things:
 a general algorithm that will perform homotopic deformations from one representation to another,
 and a different algorithm that will show when this is not possible,
 and why.
 For example,
 say I have some code written in C++,
 and I want to port it to Java.
 One way to accomplish this is to use the Atomese as the intermediate representation,
 and have compilers from Atomese to Java,
 and a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

disassembler
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from C++ to Atomese.
 This is a bit brute–force,
 but it should work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More abstractly,
 I want to morph structure perceived by the sensory system into any one of a number of different Atomese formats.
 Atomese has no preferred representational form;
 there are many that are possible.
 They're generally interchangable,
 and one can morph on representation to another.
 Except when one can't.
 I want to get a handle on that variability,
 and control it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you don't understand the previous paragraph,
 here is a concrete example.
 If one has some C code,
 one can compile it with –O0,
 –O2 and –O3 flags,
 each providing a different amount of optimization.
 The functional results are the same.
 The performance is not.
 Register assignments and assembly code is radically different.
 The compiler can guarantee the homotopic equivalence of the optimized and non–optimized versions of the assembly,
 because it is applying a large collection of graph rewrite rules to perform each optimization,
 in turn.
 Now,
 if one wanted to be perverse,
 one could generate billions of equivalent binaries,
 identical in function but differing in assembly,
 by simply choosing to randomly apply each optimization,
 or not,
 at that one location where it could be applied.
 This would generate a combinatoric explosion of possibilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compiler people would never do this,
 because it's insane.
 They have one goal:
 make the code run as fast as possible,
 period.
 For Atomese,
 there's no sch principle.
 Sure,
 we want the representation to be small,
 and use less RAM.
 But we also want to be able to apply various operations to it,
 or perhaps perform queries on it,
 and this requires a non–minimal graph.
 Perhaps the Atomese represents an algorithm,
 and we want to vectorize it.
