The contact geometry approach
\series default
.
 For thermodynamic systems with dissipation,
 standard statistical mechanics of conservative systems relies on symplectic geometry of phase space.
 For a class of nonconservative systems stemming from contact geometry,
 one can find generalized Hamilton's equations,
 a Liouville theorem,
 and microcanonical and canonical measures invariant under the contact flow.
 Remarkably,
 this canonical measure has a power–law density distribution with respect to the standard contact volume form.
 Contact geometry is the odd–dimensional cousin of symplectic geometry and naturally includes thermodynamic variables —
 temperature,
 entropy —
 as coordinates.
 This is a serious research program,
